    seoTitle: "What a Trailer Is For: How to Make a Film Trailer | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "How to make a film trailer starts with knowing its one job — a trailer is an ad, not a summary. Why it exists to sell, not explain, and the mindset that makes trailers work. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 1 of Cutting Your Film Trailer.",
    dek: `Before you cut a single frame, get this straight: a trailer is not a short version of your film. It's an advertisement — a piece of persuasion with exactly one job. Understand that job and every editing decision gets easier. Miss it, and you'll make the mistake that sinks most indie trailers.`,
    body: `<p>The single most common mistake indie filmmakers make with their trailer is treating it like a <em>summary</em> — a compressed retelling that walks through the plot from beginning to end, showing a little of everything so viewers "know what happens." That instinct is completely wrong, and it produces flat, boring trailers that give the film away and make no one want to watch it. Here's the reframe that changes everything: <strong>a trailer is an advertisement, and its only job is to make someone want to see the movie.</strong> Not to explain the movie. Not to be fair to the movie. Not to show all your best scenes. To create <em>desire.</em> A great trailer is a promise and a tease — it shows you just enough to spark a question you need answered, an emotion you want more of, a world you want to spend two hours in, and then it stops, deliberately, leaving you wanting. Once you internalize that you're making a persuasion tool and not a mini-film, everything downstream — what to include, what to hide, how to structure it, where to cut — flows from one question: does this make them want to watch?</p>

<h2>What the job actually demands</h2>

<p>If desire is the goal, here's what that means in practice:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Sell, don't summarize.</b> You are not obligated to represent the whole plot. Show the hook, the tone, the promise — and leave the story to the film itself.</li>
  <li><b>Never spoil.</b> The twist, the ending, the big reveal — these belong in the movie, not the trailer. A trailer that answers its own questions has no reason for anyone to watch.</li>
  <li><b>Sell the feeling, not the facts.</b> Audiences decide to watch based on emotion — excitement, dread, laughter, curiosity — far more than plot details. Lead with how it feels.</li>
  <li><b>Promise a genre and a tone.</b> In seconds, the trailer must tell viewers what <em>kind</em> of experience this is — horror, comedy, thriller, drama — so the right audience leans in.</li>
  <li><b>Leave them wanting.</b> The best trailers end on a question or a jolt, not a resolution. The final beat should make stopping feel unbearable.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The persuasion mindset</h2>

<p>The reason this matters so much is that your trailer is, for most of your potential audience, <strong>the entire film as far as they're concerned</strong> — it's the two minutes that decide whether they ever give you the other ninety. You can make a brilliant movie and still have almost no one see it because the trailer didn't make them care; and modest films punch far above their weight when the trailer sells them well. So the trailer isn't an afterthought you throw together once the film is done — it's arguably the most important piece of marketing you'll ever cut, and it deserves the same craft you gave the film. Approaching it as an ad also frees you creatively: you're allowed to reorder events, to pull a line from the end and use it at the start, to imply things the film delivers differently, to build an emotional arc that isn't the film's actual plot arc, all in service of desire. A trailer editor isn't being unfaithful to the film by doing this — they're doing their job, which is persuasion, not documentation. Keep that north star in view through every chapter ahead: we'll cover structure, selects, music, pacing, sound, and release, but every technique serves this one purpose. When you're deep in the edit and unsure whether a shot earns its place, don't ask "is this an important part of the story?" Ask "does this make them want to watch?" That question is the whole course in six words. Next, we'll sort out the family of formats — teaser, trailer, TV spot, clip — so you know exactly which tool you're building and why.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A trailer isn't a short version of your film — it's an ad for it. Its only job is to make someone want to watch. Not to explain, not to be fair, not to show everything. To create desire, and then stop.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first trailer was a disaster and I didn't know why. I'd walked through the whole plot in order, showed my "best" scenes, even hinted at the ending — and it was lifeless. A festival programmer watched it and said one thing: "You told me the story. You forgot to make me want it." I recut it as an ad — opened on the most intriguing image, sold the mood, buried the plot, ended on an unanswered question — same footage, and suddenly people asked when they could see the film. That day I stopped making mini-movies and started making advertisements.</p>
</div>`,
