    seoTitle: "Anatomy of a Great Trailer: Film Trailer Structure | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Film trailer structure explained — the hook, the build, and the button that every great trailer is built from, and how the beats fit together. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 3 of Cutting Your Film Trailer.",
    dek: `Great trailers aren't random highlight reels — they follow a shape as reliable as a song. Hook, build, button, with a hard beat that pivots the whole thing. Learn the anatomy and you'll never again stare at a timeline wondering what goes where.`,
    body: `<p>Watch a hundred good trailers and you'll notice they share a skeleton — not because trailer editors are unoriginal, but because this shape <em>works</em> on human attention. It grabs you, it escalates, and it leaves you hanging, and it does so in a rhythm the audience feels even if they can't name it. Learning this anatomy is like a songwriter learning verse-chorus-bridge: it's not a cage, it's a foundation you can play with once you know it. For an indie editor staring at hours of footage, it's the single most useful thing to internalize, because it turns "what do I even put where?" into a series of answerable questions. <strong>The classic trailer shape is: a hook that seizes attention, a build that raises intrigue and stakes, a hard turn that pivots the tone, an escalating montage, and a button that leaves them wanting.</strong> Let me break down each piece.</p>

<h2>The beats of a trailer</h2>

<p>The anatomy, in order:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>The hook (first 5–15 sec).</b> The opening must grab instantly — an arresting image, an intriguing line, a mood. In the scroll era you have seconds to stop someone leaving. Never open slow or with logos; open with your best bait.</li>
  <li><b>The setup / build.</b> Establish the world, the character, and the promise. Calmer, quieter, laying in just enough context and emotional investment that the audience starts to care. This is where the premise lands.</li>
  <li><b>The turn (the "drop").</b> A hard pivot — usually on a music beat, a smash cut, a title card, a line — where the trailer flips from setup into intensity. This is the spine of the whole thing; everything before builds to it, everything after rides it.</li>
  <li><b>The escalation.</b> After the turn, a rising montage: faster cuts, bigger moments, the stakes and energy climbing. Music drives it. This is where you deliver on the promise and thrill them.</li>
  <li><b>The button.</b> The final beat — a last laugh, a scare, a shocking image, a killer line — that lands after the title and leaves a lasting taste. The button is what people remember and repeat.</li>
  <li><b>Title &amp; info.</b> Your title card, and (briefly) any festival laurels, release date, or credits — placed so they don't kill momentum, usually near the end around the button.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Structure as a starting point</h2>

<p>The reason this anatomy is so powerful is that it gives your footage a <strong>job for every piece</strong>: your most arresting shot becomes a candidate for the hook, your best world-building material feeds the setup, your single most electric moment or line becomes the turn, your action and emotional peaks fuel the escalation, and your funniest or most haunting beat becomes the button. Suddenly the overwhelming pile of footage sorts itself into roles. That said, treat the structure as a foundation, not a formula to slavishly copy — the beats can stretch, compress, or reorder to fit your film. A quiet drama's "turn" might be an emotional gut-punch rather than an explosion; a comedy might have three small buttons instead of one big escalation; a teaser might be almost all hook and mood with no real build at all. The point isn't to force every film into an action-trailer template — it's to understand <em>why</em> each beat exists (grab, invest, pivot, thrill, linger) so you can honor the function while adapting the form to your story and tone. Internalize the anatomy and you gain two things at once: a map for where to put your material, and the judgment to know when to break the map. Every trailer you cut from here will be a conversation between this reliable shape and your film's specific personality. With the anatomy understood, the last foundation chapter turns you into a student of the craft — learning to watch trailers analytically so you're constantly stealing from the best.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Hook, build, turn, escalation, button. Great trailers share a skeleton because it works on human attention — learn it not as a cage but as a foundation you can play once you know the tune.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The first time the anatomy clicked for me, I was drowning in a 90-minute edit with no idea how to trailer it. A mentor had me sort clips into five buckets: hook, build, turn, escalation, button. Within an hour the trailer had a shape — my strongest image up top, the premise in the middle, our one jaw-drop moment as the turn, the peaks stacked after it, and a quiet devastating final line as the button. It wasn't magic; it was just knowing what each beat was <em>for</em>. Now I sort every trailer into those buckets before I cut a frame. It's the fastest way out of the blank-timeline paralysis.</p>
</div>`,
