    dek: `The best trailer training on earth is free and endless: the thousands of trailers already out there. But you have to watch them differently — not as a viewer being sold to, but as an editor taking the machine apart to see how it works. Here's how to study trailers so they make you better.`,
    body: `<p>Here's the best news in this whole course: your training material is unlimited, free, and available right now. Every trailer ever made is a finished, professional example you can study, and the great trailer editors are, almost without exception, obsessive students of other people's trailers. But there's a catch — <strong>watching a trailer as a normal viewer teaches you nothing, because a good trailer is designed to make you feel, not analyze.</strong> To learn from it you have to switch modes: stop letting it work on you and start taking it apart, asking at every moment "what did they just do to me, and how?" This is the difference between consuming trailers and studying them, and it's a skill you can build deliberately. Do it for a few months and you'll develop an instinct for pacing, structure, and emotional manipulation that no article can teach.</p>

<h2>How to dissect a trailer</h2>

<p>When you sit down to study one, do this:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Watch it once as a viewer.</b> Let it work on you first. Note your gut reaction — where you leaned in, where you felt the jolt, where you decided you'd watch the film. Those feelings are the data.</li>
  <li><b>Now find the beats.</b> Watch again and mark the anatomy: where's the hook, the build, the turn, the escalation, the button? Time them. Notice how long the setup runs before the drop hits.</li>
  <li><b>Study the music and sound.</b> When does the music enter, build, and drop out? Where are the silences and the "brraams" and risers? Trailer editors cut to music — reverse-engineer that relationship.</li>
  <li><b>Count and feel the cuts.</b> Notice how the cutting speeds up toward the climax and how shot length controls tension. Watch a section muted to feel pure rhythm.</li>
  <li><b>Ask what they hid.</b> What did the trailer <em>not</em> show? How did it imply story without spoiling? Learning what to withhold is as important as what to include.</li>
  <li><b>Study the openings and buttons.</b> The first 10 seconds and the final beat are the hardest-worked parts of any trailer. Collect great hooks and great buttons specifically.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Build a swipe file</h2>

<p>The habit that turns casual study into real skill is keeping a <strong>swipe file</strong> — a running collection of trailers, and moments within trailers, that did something you admire, with a note on <em>why</em>. A hook that grabbed you instantly, a music drop that gave you chills, a title reveal that landed, a button that made you laugh out loud, a clever way a drama built tension without action. When you're stuck on your own trailer, this file becomes a bank of proven solutions you can adapt (not copy) to your film. Focus your study especially on trailers for films <em>like yours</em> — similar genre, tone, scale, and budget — because a micro-budget horror trailer has far more to teach you than a $200M blockbuster's, which had resources you'll never have. The indie and festival trailer world is full of editors doing extraordinary work with modest footage, and those are your real teachers. Also study trailers you think are <em>bad</em>, and articulate why they didn't work — a slow open, a spoiled ending, a mismatched tone, a weak button — because learning to diagnose failure sharpens your eye as much as admiring success. Over time this analytical watching rewires how you see: you'll catch yourself in a cinema instinctively clocking the turn in a trailer, feeling the cut rhythm, noticing the withhold. That instinct, built from hundreds of dissected examples, is what separates editors who follow rules from editors who have taste. There's no shortcut to it, but there's no gatekeeper either — just you, a screen, and the willingness to watch like an editor instead of an audience. That completes your foundations. From here the course gets hands-on, and it starts where every real trailer starts: digging through your own footage for gold.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Watching a trailer as a viewer teaches you nothing — it's built to make you feel, not think. Learn to take it apart: what did they just do to me, and how? Do that for months and you build taste no article can give you.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I keep a folder of maybe forty trailers I've torn apart frame by frame, each with a note: "watch how the music drops out completely before the button" or "the whole first act is one unbroken tension build, no cuts faster than three seconds." When I'm stuck, I don't stare at my timeline — I open the folder and remind myself how someone solved a similar problem. None of it is copying; it's studying the masters the way painters study in galleries. The trailers are the textbook, and it's free. Most people just never open it.</p>
</div>`,
