    dek: `Before you cut anything, you mine. A trailer is built from your film's best individual moments — the striking images, the killer lines, the emotional peaks — and finding and organizing those "selects" is the unglamorous groundwork that makes the actual cutting fast and inspired.`,
    body: `<p>Great trailers feel effortless, but that ease is built on a foundation of grunt work: watching your entire film with a trailer-editor's eye and pulling out every single moment that could earn a place. These are your <strong>selects</strong> — the raw ore you'll refine into the finished trailer. The mistake beginners make is skipping this step and trying to cut the trailer straight from the film's timeline, scrubbing back and forth hunting for that one shot they half-remember. That's slow, frustrating, and worst of all it means you cut from a narrow, forgetful sense of what you have. When you do the selects pass properly, the opposite happens: you sit down to cut with a curated pile of your film's absolute best material at your fingertips, and the trailer almost assembles itself. This chapter is about doing that pass well, because <strong>the quality of your selects sets the ceiling on the quality of your trailer.</strong></p>

<h2>What to pull</h2>

<p>As you watch your film, harvest everything in these categories:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Striking images.</b> The most beautiful, arresting, or unusual shots — anything that stops the eye. These are hook and button candidates and the visual texture of your trailer.</li>
  <li><b>Great lines.</b> Every quotable, intriguing, funny, or chilling piece of dialogue. A single perfect line can anchor a whole trailer. Pull them even out of context.</li>
  <li><b>Emotional peaks.</b> The moments of highest feeling — a breakdown, a triumph, a scare, a kiss, a laugh. Trailers sell emotion, so these are gold.</li>
  <li><b>Motion &amp; energy.</b> Action, movement, dynamic camera, anything with kinetic punch to drive your escalation. Even in a quiet film, find the moments with momentum.</li>
  <li><b>Tone-setters.</b> Shots and beats that instantly communicate your genre and mood — the images that say "this is a horror" or "this is a tender drama" without a word.</li>
  <li><b>Faces &amp; character.</b> Compelling close-ups and reactions. Audiences connect to people; a great face doing something is often stronger than any plot beat.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Organize so you can find gold fast</h2>

<p>Pulling the selects is half the job; <strong>organizing them so they're instantly usable is the other half.</strong> Dump everything into a dedicated selects bin, separate from your film's edit, and then — this is the key move — sort them into categories or sub-bins that match how you'll use them: a bin for great lines, one for striking images, one for emotional peaks, one for action, one for tone/mood, one for possible hooks, one for possible buttons. When you then sit down to build the trailer around the anatomy from Chapter 3, you're not hunting through raw footage; you're shopping from labeled shelves. Two disciplines make this pass pay off. First, be generous in what you pull but ruthless later — grab anything that <em>might</em> work now, because it's cheap to collect and you can always discard, but a moment you didn't pull is a moment you'll forget exists. Second, watch for material the film uses one way that a trailer could use another: a line delivered quietly in context might become a chilling voiceover over different images; an establishing shot might become your hook; a throwaway reaction might become your button. Trailer editing is recombination, and the selects pass is where you free each moment from its place in the story so you can redeploy it. Yes, this pass is tedious — watching your own film yet again, scrubbing and marking and labeling — but it is the single highest-leverage hour you'll spend, because everything downstream is faster and better when your best material is curated and at hand. Cut from a great selects bin and the trailer flows; cut from raw footage and you'll fight it the whole way. With your gold mined and sorted, the next chapter starts assembling it into the three-act structure.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The quality of your selects sets the ceiling on your trailer. Mine your film for every great image, line, and emotional peak, free each from its place in the story, and sort it onto labeled shelves — then the trailer almost cuts itself.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I used to cut trailers straight off the film's timeline, and I'd waste hours going "where was that shot?" and settling for the third-best version because I couldn't find the best. Then I forced myself to do a proper selects pass: one full watch, pulling every candidate into bins labeled lines, images, peaks, action, tone. It took an afternoon and felt like a chore — until I started cutting and realized the trailer was basically assembling itself from my shelves. I've never gone back. The selects pass feels like the slow part, but it's what makes the fun part fast.</p>
</div>`,
