    body: `<p>In Chapter 3 you learned the beats; now you build with them. The classic full-trailer shape maps neatly onto three acts, and thinking of it this way gives you a concrete assembly plan for your selects. <strong>Act one establishes and intrigues, act two turns and reveals the real premise, act three escalates to a climax and a button.</strong> Each act has a different energy and a different job, and the transitions between them — especially the big turn from act one to act two — are where the trailer's power lives. The beauty of building this way is that you start rough: you're not fine-cutting yet, you're laying blocks of material into the three-act skeleton to see if the overall shape and flow work. Get the structure right in broad strokes first, and the detailed cutting becomes refinement rather than invention.</p>

<h2>Laying down the three acts</h2>

<p>Assemble your selects into this build:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Act one — establish &amp; hook.</b> Open on your strongest hook, then set up the world, tone, and central character. Calmer and cleaner; give the audience just enough to care. This act ends by posing the question the film answers.</li>
  <li><b>The turn.</b> The hinge of the trailer. A hard beat — a music drop, a title, a shocking image or line — that flips act one's setup into act two's intensity. This single moment does more work than any other; make it land.</li>
  <li><b>Act two — reveal &amp; raise.</b> After the turn, open up the real premise and stakes. Show more of the conflict, the threat, the promise. Energy rises, cuts quicken, the music builds. The audience now understands what they'd be watching.</li>
  <li><b>Act three — escalate &amp; climax.</b> The peak. Rapid-fire your biggest moments — action, emotion, spectacle — building to a crescendo. This is the payoff that delivers on everything the trailer promised.</li>
  <li><b>The button &amp; title.</b> After the climax, land your title card, then hit the final button — a last laugh, scare, or line that leaves a lasting impression. End on a high, not a fade.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Build rough, then refine</h2>

<p>The most important discipline in this phase is to <strong>resist perfectionism and build the whole thing rough first.</strong> Drop your best hook at the top, block in the setup, place your turn, stack your escalation, drop the button — get a complete, ugly, timing-approximate version of the entire trailer before you polish a single cut. Why? Because a trailer is about overall shape and momentum, and you can only judge those when the whole thing exists. If you obsess over frame-perfect cuts in act one before you've built act three, you'll waste hours polishing material that the finished structure might not even need. So think of your first pass as sculpting with big blocks: does the trailer build? Does the turn hit? Does it end strong? Does it feel too long or too short? Fix the structure at that level — move the turn earlier, cut a saggy stretch, swap a weak hook — and only once the skeleton is sound do you go back and fine-cut. Two things to watch as you build. First, the turn's placement controls everything: too late and act one drags; too early and you've got nothing to build to. Feel for the moment the audience is invested enough to be jolted. Second, protect the momentum — a trailer should feel like it's always moving toward something, never plateauing, so if a section sags, it's usually a sign that stretch needs tightening or a stronger select. And remember from Chapter 1: you're free to reorder your film's actual events completely. The turn might use a moment from your film's climax; act one might use its ending's imagery. Serve the trailer's arc, not the film's chronology. Once the three-act structure is standing and the shape feels right, it's ready for the element that will bind it all together and dictate its final rhythm — music, which is next.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Build the whole trailer rough before you polish a single cut. A trailer is about shape and momentum, and you can only judge those once the entire skeleton — hook, turn, escalation, button — is standing.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I lost a whole day once frame-perfecting the first thirty seconds of a trailer, making act one gorgeous — then realized the structure was broken and cut half of it. Painful lesson. Now I block the entire trailer rough first, ugly cuts and all, in maybe an hour: hook, setup, turn, escalation, button. Only when the shape works — when I can feel it building and landing — do I go back and refine. The rough pass tells me the truth about the structure while it's still cheap to change. Polish before structure is just decorating a house with a cracked foundation.</p>
</div>`,
