    desc: "Music is the engine of a trailer — choosing it and cutting to it",
    time: "8 min",
    moduleKey: "core",
    kicker: "Core Craft",
    seoTitle: "Music & the Trailer's Engine: Film Trailer Music | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Film trailer music is the engine — how to choose a track, cut to its beats and drops, and license it legally so your trailer drives emotion without a copyright strike. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 7 of Cutting Your Film Trailer.",
    dek: `If a trailer has a secret weapon, it's music. The track sets the emotion, dictates the pace, and provides the beats you cut to. Choose the right one and the trailer half-edits itself; choose wrong and no amount of clever cutting saves it. Here's how to pick it, cut to it, and clear it legally.`,
    body: `<p>Ask any trailer editor what matters most and they'll say the same thing: the music. A trailer's music isn't a backing track you lay under a finished cut — it's the <strong>engine that drives the whole piece</strong>, and in fact most trailer editors choose the track first and cut the picture <em>to</em> it. The track sets the emotional temperature, provides the rhythm you edit to, and — crucially — supplies the structure: its quiet intro is your setup, its big drop is your turn, its climax is your escalation. When picture and music are locked together, cuts landing on beats and images swelling with the music, the trailer feels inevitable and powerful. When they're fighting, or when the music is just wallpaper, even great footage falls flat. So this is one of the highest-leverage decisions you'll make, and it deserves real time. Let me cover choosing it, cutting to it, and — the part indies must not skip — clearing it legally.</p>

<h2>Working with trailer music</h2>

<p>How to make music do its job:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Choose the track first.</b> Find your music before or alongside your rough cut, not after. Let its structure — intro, build, drop, climax — become the trailer's structure. The right track makes the edit obvious.</li>
  <li><b>Match emotion, not just genre.</b> The track must carry the exact feeling you want — dread, wonder, adrenaline, heartbreak. A technically epic track that's the wrong emotion will missell your film. Trust the feeling in your gut.</li>
  <li><b>Cut to the beats.</b> Land your hard cuts, reveals, and title on the music's beats and hits. Editing on the beat is what makes a trailer feel tight and intentional rather than loose.</li>
  <li><b>Use the drop as your turn.</b> Align the track's biggest moment — the bass drop, the key change, the swell — with your trailer's turn. Picture and music hitting hard together is the single most powerful move in trailer editing.</li>
  <li><b>Use silence.</b> A sudden cut to near-silence before the drop, or a beat of quiet before the button, is a pro move. Dynamics — loud, soft, loud — create impact. Don't run the music flat-out the whole time.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Clear it, or it can't leave your laptop</h2>

<p>Here's the trap that catches almost every indie, and I need to be blunt about it: <strong>you cannot legally release a trailer with commercial music you haven't licensed.</strong> That gorgeous popular song or famous score you dropped on your rough cut? Using it publicly — on YouTube, social, anywhere — without a license is copyright infringement, and at minimum your trailer gets muted or taken down by an automated content-ID claim, at worst you face a real legal problem. This is not a technicality you can ignore because you're small; content-ID bots don't care about your budget. So build your trailer with legally clearable music from the start. Your real options: <em>royalty-free and licensed trailer-music libraries</em> (there are excellent ones built specifically for this, full of "trailerized" tracks with the builds and drops you need), <em>music you commission or that a composer friend makes for you</em> (clean rights, custom-fit — see the Working with a Composer course), or <em>properly licensed tracks</em> where you actually pay for the sync rights. What you cannot do is grab a Hollywood trailer's music or a chart song and hope no one notices. A smart workflow is to edit with a temp track that has the vibe you want, then replace it with a cleared library track of similar structure before release — just don't fall so in love with the temp that the cleared version disappoints (a trap the composer course calls "temp love"). The Music Licensing course covers the legal side in depth, and it's worth reading before you release anything. Get your music both emotionally right and legally clean, and your trailer has its engine. With the track chosen and locked, the next chapter is about the finer craft of cutting to it — pacing, rhythm, and building tension.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Most trailer editors choose the music first and cut the picture to it. The track is the engine — its intro is your setup, its drop is your turn. But if you haven't licensed it, it can't leave your laptop.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I cut a trailer I was proud of to a famous film score — it was electric. Then I uploaded it and within minutes it was muted by a content-ID claim, dead on arrival. Lesson learned the hard way. Now I edit to a temp for feel, but I choose a clearable library track with the same shape early, and I finish on that. The good trailer-music libraries are so deep now that you can find a legit track with the exact build and drop you need. The music makes the trailer — but only if you're actually allowed to use it.</p>
</div>`,
