    seoTitle: "Voiceover, Sound Design & Mix for Trailers | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Trailer voiceover and sound design — how risers, hits, whooshes, silence, and a strong mix make a trailer punch, and when a voiceover helps or hurts. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 10 of Cutting Your Film Trailer.",
    dek: `Music is the engine, but the rest of the soundtrack is what makes a trailer <em>hit</em>: the risers that build dread, the boom on the title drop, the whoosh between cuts, the sudden silence before the scare. Plus the question of voiceover, and a final mix that ties it all together.`,
    body: `<p>If you strip a great trailer down to just its music, it loses half its power — because a huge amount of a trailer's punch comes from <strong>sound design</strong>, the layer of non-musical audio that makes moments land physically. The deep boom on the title reveal, the rising riser that tightens your chest before the drop, the whoosh that carries a cut, the sub-bass hit under an impact, the sudden cut to silence before a scare — these are the trailer editor's percussion, and they're what make an audience <em>feel</em> the trailer in their body, not just watch it. This layer is often what separates a trailer that feels flat from one that feels cinematic, and it's very achievable on a budget because trailer sound-design element libraries (risers, hits, whooshes, booms, drones) are cheap and plentiful. This chapter covers those elements, the voiceover question, and the mix that ties everything together.</p>

<h2>The trailer sound toolkit</h2>

<p>The elements that give a trailer physical impact:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Hits &amp; booms.</b> Deep impact sounds on your hard cuts, title reveal, and big reveals. The "boom" on the title drop is a trailer signature — it makes the moment feel monumental. Land them on the beat with the picture.</li>
  <li><b>Risers.</b> Sounds that rise in pitch and intensity to build tension before a drop or reveal. A well-placed riser under your build makes the release hit ten times harder. Time the peak to your turn.</li>
  <li><b>Whooshes &amp; transitions.</b> Swishes that carry the eye across a cut, especially through fast montages. Used tastefully they smooth and energize; overused they get cheesy, so be selective.</li>
  <li><b>Drones &amp; atmospheres.</b> Low, sustained tones under quiet sections that create unease or tension without music. Great for a horror or thriller's setup, filling "silence" with dread.</li>
  <li><b>Silence.</b> The most underrated sound tool. A hard cut to total silence before a scare or a drop creates a vacuum the next sound fills explosively. Dynamics — loud, silent, loud — are everything.</li>
  <li><b>Keep the best film audio.</b> Pull the most impactful diegetic sounds from your film — a gunshot, a scream, a slam, a laugh — and feature them. Real sound from your movie grounds the designed elements.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Voiceover, and the mix that finishes it</h2>

<p>On <strong>voiceover</strong>: the classic "In a world…" narration has largely fallen out of fashion, and for most indie films you should skip it — a VO is hard to write well, harder to perform without sounding cheesy, and a bad one instantly cheapens a trailer. Let your images, your film's own dialogue, and text cards carry the story instead; a well-chosen line of your actual dialogue as a voiceover bed is far more powerful and authentic than scripted narration. That said, voiceover can work for specific genres and tones — a noir, a documentary, a comedy with an ironic narrator — and if your film genuinely calls for it, invest in a good voice and good writing, or don't do it at all. Then comes the <strong>mix</strong>, which ties the whole soundtrack together and is where amateur trailers most often fall apart. You've got music, sound-design elements, film dialogue, and maybe VO all competing, and if they're not balanced, the result is a muddy, harsh mess where nothing is clear and the loud parts distort. The keys: make sure dialogue and key lines are always intelligible (duck the music under them), give the music room to breathe as the emotional bed, place your hits and risers so they punch without swamping everything, use the full dynamic range (quiet sections genuinely quiet so loud sections feel loud), and — critically — <em>watch your levels</em> so nothing clips and distorts. Reference the mix against professional trailers at the same volume, and check it on multiple systems (good speakers, laptop speakers, phone, earbuds) because your trailer will be heard on all of them and a mix that only works on studio monitors will sound terrible in a phone feed. The Sound Design course goes deeper on mixing principles if you want them. A trailer with rich sound design and a clean, punchy mix feels professional and hits hard; one with music alone and a muddy mix feels flat no matter how well it's cut. With picture, text, and sound all locked, your trailer is essentially finished — the final chapter covers cutting it for different platforms and getting it out into the world.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Sound design is the trailer editor's percussion — the boom on the title, the riser before the drop, the cut to silence before the scare. It's what makes an audience feel the trailer in their body, not just watch it.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I once compared my trailer, cut to just music, against a friend's that had full sound design — same caliber of footage. Mine felt fine; theirs felt like a real movie trailer. The difference was entirely the sound layer: a riser building into the turn, a deep boom on the title, a beat of dead silence before the button. I bought a cheap trailer sound-effects pack, spent an evening laying in risers, hits, and whooshes, mixed it so nothing clipped, and my trailer transformed. Music is the engine, but sound design is the punch you feel in your chest. Don't stop at the music.</p>
</div>`,
