    dek: `Your beautiful 2-minute horizontal trailer is perfect for exactly one place. Everywhere else — Instagram, TikTok, festival submissions, ads — wants a different length, shape, or hook. This chapter is about reshaping your master trailer into the versions each platform actually rewards.`,
    body: `<p>Here's a reality that trips up filmmakers who spent weeks perfecting one trailer: <strong>the platform decides the format, and your master trailer is only right for a couple of them.</strong> A 2-minute 16:9 trailer is ideal on YouTube or your website, where people choose to watch and settle in. But drop that same file into an Instagram or TikTok feed — vertical, sound-off by default, scrolled past in a second — and it dies, because it's the wrong shape, too long, and its hook assumes an attention it doesn't have. The modern reality is that most people will first encounter your film not on YouTube but in a social feed, on a phone, vertically, muted, while scrolling fast. If your only trailer is the horizontal two-minute epic, you're invisible where the audience actually is. So the final creative task is reshaping your master into platform-native versions — and the good news is you've already done the hard part; this is derivation, not creation.</p>

<h2>Versions to cut</h2>

<p>From your master trailer, derive:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>The master (16:9, 1:30–2:30).</b> Your full trailer, for YouTube, your website, festivals, and press. This is the one you already built — the source for everything else.</li>
  <li><b>Vertical / square social cuts (9:16 or 1:1, 15–60 sec).</b> Reframed vertical or square, drastically shortened, hook in the first second. This is where discovery happens now — arguably your most important version for reach.</li>
  <li><b>The hook-first micro-cut (6–15 sec).</b> An ultra-short teaser that leads with your single most arresting moment. For feeds where you have one second to stop the scroll. Front-load everything; there's no time to build.</li>
  <li><b>Captioned versions.</b> Social video plays muted by default, so burn in captions for any dialogue or key text. A trailer that only works with sound on loses most of its social audience.</li>
  <li><b>Ad cuts (15–30 sec).</b> Tight, punchy versions optimized for paid placement, ending clearly on your title and where-to-watch. Often several variants to test.</li>
  <li><b>Festival/press deliverables.</b> Whatever specs a festival or outlet requires — resolution, aspect, length, format. Read their specs and deliver exactly to them.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Reframe, re-hook, re-time</h2>

<p>Three adjustments turn your master into a platform-native cut, and skipping any of them kills it. First, <strong>reframe for the aspect ratio.</strong> Going from 16:9 to 9:16 vertical isn't just cropping the middle — you have to re-center each shot so the important action stays in frame, sometimes scaling or repositioning per shot. A face cropped to a forehead, or your title running off the edge, screams "lazy repurpose." Take the time to reframe shot by shot. Second, <strong>re-hook for the scroll.</strong> Feed videos live or die in the first second, so your social cuts can't use the slow-burn hook that works on YouTube where people have committed to watching — they need to open on your single most gripping image or moment, immediately, before anyone scrolls past. Often the best social hook is a moment you'd never open your full trailer with, but that stops a thumb. Third, <strong>re-time for the length and the mute.</strong> Ruthlessly shorten — a 15-second cut isn't a trimmed 2-minute trailer, it's a different piece built from your two or three best beats — and make sure it reads with the sound off via captions and strong visuals. The overarching principle: <em>don't make one trailer and dump it everywhere; make one master and reshape it for where each version lives.</em> It's more work, but it's derivation from material you've already crafted, and it's the difference between a trailer that reaches people and one that sits unwatched on a YouTube page. Meet the audience where they are, in the shape and length that platform rewards, and your film gets seen. With every version cut, only one step remains — testing, finishing, and actually launching your trailer into the world, which is where we finish.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Don't make one trailer and dump it everywhere. Make one master and reshape it — reframe for vertical, re-hook for the scroll, re-time for the mute. Meet the audience where they actually are: on a phone, in a feed, sound off.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I used to post my horizontal trailer to every platform and wonder why social did nothing. Then I actually watched how people use their phones — vertical, muted, thumb moving — and it was obvious. Now from every master I cut a vertical version, reframed shot by shot, captioned, opening on the single most arresting second, trimmed to fifteen. That version routinely outperforms the "real" trailer by a mile on social, because it's built for where people are instead of asking them to come to me. Same footage, right shape. The reshape is where the reach lives.</p>
</div>`,
