    dek: `The last mile: showing your trailer to fresh eyes before you commit, finishing and exporting it clean, and launching it into the world with intent. A great trailer that's released badly still fails — here's how to give yours its best shot at landing.`,
    body: `<p>You've cut a trailer you're proud of — but you're the worst possible judge of it, because you've seen your footage a thousand times and you know what happens. You can't feel your own trailer the way a stranger will, and that stranger is the only audience that matters. So before you release anything, you <strong>test it on fresh eyes</strong> — people who don't know the film — and watch not what they say but how they react. Then you finish it properly and launch it with a plan. This final chapter closes the loop from Chapter 1: the whole point was to make people want to watch your film, and testing tells you whether you succeeded while you can still fix it, finishing makes it look professional, and a thoughtful release gives it the reach it deserves. Let me walk the last mile.</p>

<h2>Test, finish, launch</h2>

<p>The steps to the finish line:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Show it to fresh eyes.</b> Screen it for people unfamiliar with the film and watch their faces, not their words. Did they lean in? Get bored? Where did attention drift? Do they want to see the film? Their honest reactions are your final edit notes.</li>
  <li><b>Ask the one question.</b> After watching, ask: "Do you want to see this movie?" and "What's it about?" If they don't want to see it, the trailer failed its job. If they describe the wrong film, you're misselling the tone.</li>
  <li><b>Revise, don't defend.</b> Resist explaining your choices. If testers consistently drift at the same spot or miss the hook, fix it — the audience is always right about their own experience, even when they can't articulate why.</li>
  <li><b>Finish clean.</b> Lock the edit, do a final color and sound pass so the trailer looks and sounds polished, confirm your title and info cards are correct, and check it plays flawlessly start to finish.</li>
  <li><b>Export properly.</b> Render high-quality masters for each platform at the right specs — resolution, aspect, codec, loudness. Keep the project archived so you can make revisions and additional cuts later.</li>
  <li><b>Launch with intent.</b> Don't just upload and hope. Pick your timing, write a strong title and thumbnail, seed it across your platforms and versions at once, and make sure every viewer has a clear next step — where and when to watch the film.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The trailer is a promise — now keep the whole course</h2>

<p>A few final tips for the finish and release, and then a look back at everything you've built. On <strong>the thumbnail and title</strong> (for YouTube especially): they do as much work as the trailer itself in getting the click, so craft a compelling thumbnail from your most striking frame and a title that intrigues — a trailer no one clicks might as well not exist. On <strong>the call to action</strong>: every trailer should make crystal clear what to do next — "In theaters March," "Streaming now," a link, a festival date — because you spent two minutes creating desire and it's wasted if people don't know how to act on it. On <strong>timing and consistency</strong>: release when your audience is actually there and your film is available or close, and keep your visual identity (title treatment, tone, key art) consistent across the trailer, thumbnails, poster, and social so the whole campaign feels like one film. And a note of realism: not every trailer lands, testing sometimes reveals the trailer needs a real recut, and that's normal — the great trailer editors iterate, test, and revise rather than nailing it first try, so treat feedback as fuel, not failure. Now step back. Across this course you learned that a trailer is an advertisement whose only job is desire; you learned its formats, anatomy, and how to study the masters; you mined your footage for selects and built them into a three-act structure; you made music the engine and mastered pacing; you added text, sound design, and a clean mix; you reshaped it for every platform; and now you test, finish, and launch. That is the complete craft of the trailer editor, and it rests on one idea from the very first chapter that's worth carrying out the door: <strong>everything serves the question "does this make them want to watch?"</strong> Answer that at every step, and your trailer will do its job — turning strangers into an audience for the film you worked so hard to make. Go cut a trailer that makes people <em>need</em> to see your movie. Congratulations on finishing the course.</p>

<div class="pullquote">You're the worst judge of your own trailer — you know what happens. Test it on fresh eyes, watch their faces not their words, and ask the only question that matters: do you want to see this movie?</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I was certain a trailer was perfect until I showed it to three people who didn't know the film. All three drifted at the same 40-second stretch, and none could tell me what the movie was about. My ego wanted to explain; instead I recut — killed the saggy stretch, sharpened the hook, clarified the tone. The next test group leaned in and said "when can I watch this?" That's the whole job in one sentence. Fresh eyes will tell you the truth your own eyes can't. Test before you release, every time, and let the audience's reaction — not your pride — have the final cut.</p>
</div>`,
